   All about this @pssff2019 🔥 Thanks to the crew for helping to put this
   together! If you hit up @entrepot_paris, be sure to take a look at
   @wayuptherephoto’s blow up of an #oceanrip — a rare phenomenon that
   visually resembles a hurricane. These can be deadly, and as #ocean
   temps + #currents get #warmer over time due to #climatechange, these
   may become more extreme and unpredictable. Shout out to
   @guillaumelegoff for this! #pssff2019 #reframeclimate All about this
   @pssff2019 🔥 Thanks to the crew for helping to put this together! If
   you hit up @entrepot_paris, be sure to take a look at
   @wayuptherephoto’s blow up of an #oceanrip — a rare phenomenon that
   visually resembles a hurricane. These can be deadly, and as #ocean
   temps + #currents get #warmer over time due to #climatechange, these
   may become more extreme and unpredictable. Shout out to
   @guillaumelegoff for this! #pssff2019 #reframeclimate
   📸 @tomprotti, laureate of the @prixcarmignac award which was dedicated
   to funding an investigative reportage on the #Amazon 🌎 From January to
   July 2019, Italian photojournalist Tommaso Protti, accompanied by
   British journalist Sam Cowie, travelled thousands of miles across the
   #BrazilianAmazon to create this reportage. From the eastern region of
   #Maranhão to the western region of #Rondônia, through the states of
   Pará and #Amazonas, they portrayed life in modern day Brazilian
   Amazon, where social and humanitarian crises overlap with the ongoing
   destruction of the rainforest, lungs of the planet. Caption 1/2:
   Araribóia, Brazil - A member of the Guajajara forest guard in a moment
   of sad silence at the sight of a toppled tree cut down by suspected
   illegal loggers on the Araribóia indigenous reserve in Maranhão
   state. With deep cuts to Brazil’s environmental and indigenous
   protection bodies in recent years, tribes people across the Amazon are
   increasingly forming vigilante. Caption 2/2: Grajaú, Brazil - A
   deforested area in the southern Maranhao state seen from the helicopter
   of IBAMA, Brazil’s national environmental agency. Maranhão is one of
   the worst affected by forest fires and illegal logging that has lost 75
   per cent of its Amazon forest cover. The Amazon Rainforest is losing a
   football pitch of forest cover every minute. Scientists say the Amazon
   is reaching a tipping point: if deforestation continues upward, the
   forest may never recover. @tomprotti for @fondationcarmignac
   #prixcarmignacamazonia 📸 @tomprotti, laureate of the @prixcarmignac
   award which was dedicated to funding an investigative reportage on the
   #Amazon 🌎 From January to July 2019, Italian photojournalist Tommaso
   Protti, accompanied by British journalist Sam Cowie, travelled
   thousands of miles across the #BrazilianAmazon to create this
   reportage. From the eastern region of #Maranhão to the western region
   of #Rondônia, through the states of Pará and #Amazonas, they
   portrayed life in modern day Brazilian Amazon, where social and
   humanitarian crises overlap with the ongoing destruction of the
   rainforest, lungs of the planet. Caption 1/2: Araribóia, Brazil - A
   member of the Guajajara forest guard in a moment of sad silence at the
   sight of a toppled tree cut down by suspected illegal loggers on the
   Araribóia indigenous reserve in Maranhão state. With deep cuts to
   Brazil’s environmental and indigenous protection bodies in recent
   years, tribes people across the Amazon are increasingly forming
   vigilante. Caption 2/2: Grajaú, Brazil - A deforested area in the
   southern Maranhao state seen from the helicopter of IBAMA, Brazil’s
   national environmental agency. Maranhão is one of the worst affected
   by forest fires and illegal logging that has lost 75 per cent of its
   Amazon forest cover. The Amazon Rainforest is losing a football pitch
   of forest cover every minute. Scientists say the Amazon is reaching a
   tipping point: if deforestation continues upward, the forest may never
   recover. @tomprotti for @fondationcarmignac #prixcarmignacamazonia
   It’s time to learn the FACTS on #climatechange 🌏🌍🌎 #reframeclimate
   #climatestrike #climatechangeisreal It’s time to learn the FACTS on
   #climatechange 🌏🌍🌎 #reframeclimate #climatestrike #climatechangeisreal
   To coincide with the #climatestrike, we are posting visuals that
   highlight this important issue. @paolopellegrin (@magnumphotos) has
   photographed wars in #Darfur, #Bosnia, #Sudan & #Afghanistan. However
   in 2009, Pellegrin covered something a little different - one of the
   world's most critical issues, #climatechange. In 'Water Wars,'
   Pellegrin exposes the conflict over fresh water along the Jordan River,
   where inhabitants have faced a six-year drought. In fact, water hasn't
   touched Ziglab dam's (pictured) water gauges for more than a decade.
   Scientists expect #climatechange to cut 16% of its current
   precipitation levels by 2050, consequently endangering the livelihoods
   of nearby residents who completely depend on rain to feed their crops.
   The caption of the above image: Jordan. May 2009. School children go
   and play in the Ziglab dam near Al Aziyya in northern Jordan. 📸
   @pierreterdjman To coincide with the #climatestrike, we are posting
   visuals that highlight this important issue. @paolopellegrin
   (@magnumphotos) has photographed wars in #Darfur, #Bosnia, #Sudan &
   #Afghanistan. However in 2009, Pellegrin covered something a little
   different - one of the world's most critical issues, #climatechange. In
   'Water Wars,' Pellegrin exposes the conflict over fresh water along the
   Jordan River, where inhabitants have faced a six-year drought. In fact,
   water hasn't touched Ziglab dam's (pictured) water gauges for more than
   a decade. Scientists expect #climatechange to cut 16% of its current
   precipitation levels by 2050, consequently endangering the livelihoods
   of nearby residents who completely depend on rain to feed their crops.
   The caption of the above image: Jordan. May 2009. School children go
   and play in the Ziglab dam near Al Aziyya in northern Jordan. 📸
   @pierreterdjman
   Remembering photographer and friend Stanley Greene today. The
   international photo agency @noorimages contributed the above image on
   his behalf for our important global campaign with @magnumfoundation to
   #reframeclimate. Taken in #Greenland in 2009, the photographer went
   there as part of the agency's climate stories; an effort by nine Noor
   photographers to document some of the causes and consequences, from
   deforestation to changing sea levels, as well as the people whose lives
   and jobs were impacted by the changing climate. It depicts a family of
   Inuit, commonly referred to as Eskimos, in Uummannaq. The name Eskimos
   comes from the word "Eskimautik", which means "Those who eat raw meat".
   Traditional dress of Polar bear, seal skin, boots, and fur-lined
   coverings have to help Inuit people to survive some of Earth’s coldest
   weather for centuries. Without sea ice, seals cannot build ledges on
   which to rest, eat and bear their pups; walruses cannot find refuge on
   drift ice to rest, and digest their meals; polar bears cannot catch
   seals; hunters cannot travel in dog sled. arctic biologists say that
   the entire ecosystem is about to collapse. Photo : Stanley Greene
   (@noorimages). Taken on October 21, 2009.————————————————————————
   Souvenir du photographe et ami Stanley Greene. L’agence internationale
   de photographie @noorimages a contribué à notre campagne globale avec
   @magnumfoundation pour #reframeclimate avec la photo ci-dessus En 2009,
   neuf photographes de l’agence Noor ont documenté les causes et
   conséquences du changement climatique - de la déforestation à
   l’augmentation du niveau des océans, en passant par les personnes dont
   la vie et le travail sont affectés. Cette photo de Stanley Greene au
   Groenland représente une famille d’Inuits, communément appelés
   Esquimaux, à Uummannaq. Les Inuits sont traditionnellement vêtus de
   peaux d’ours polaires et de phoques pour survivre aux conditions
   climatiques. Sans la mer de glace, les animaux n’ont nulle part où se
   reposer, manger et donner naissance à leurs petits et les chasseurs ne
   peuvent plus se déplacer. Selon les biologistes de l’Arctique, la
   totalité de cet écosystème est au bord de l’effondrement. Remembering
   photographer and friend Stanley Greene today. The international photo
   agency @noorimages contributed the above image on his behalf for our
   important global campaign with @magnumfoundation to #reframeclimate.
